The paper deals with topics related to logic, complexity theory, programming languages, and artificial intelligence. The use of the $\lambda$-calculus and logical formalization of the liar's paradox suggest that the paper may belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The discussion of NP-completeness and Cook's theorem, as well as the presentation of proofs, indicate that the paper may also belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. The mention of fuzzy logic programming and the discovery of a paradox in a system suggest that the paper may belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The discussion of NP-completeness and the Immermann-Vardi theorem suggest that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the mention of contradictions and inconsistencies in the results suggests that the paper may also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category.
